characteristics.participants:
Aimed to include 68 preterm infants undergoing planned extubation. However, the study was terminated after recruiting 6 participants.
Inclusion criteria


GA < 32 + 0 weeks;

Birthweight < 1500 g;

Received mechanical ventilation via an endotracheal tube for ≥ 120 hours;

Caffeine treatment according to unit guidelines;

paCO2< 65 mm Hg with pH > 7.2;

FiO225%‐40% to maintain SpO2at 90%–94%;

Ventilated using: 

Time‐cycled, pressure‐controlled ventilation: PIP ≤ 22 cm H2O, PEEP ≤ 6 cm H2O; or

Volume guarantee ventilation: working Ppeak ≤ 22 cm H2O, PEEP ≤ 6 cm H2O; or

High frequency oscillation ventilation: Pmean ≤ 12 cm H2O, amplitude ≤ 30 cm H2O.

Decision of the attending clinician to extubate.

Exclusion criteria


Major congenital malformation requiring surgery;

Duct‐dependent congenital heart disease;

Neuromuscular disease;

Participation in another randomised controlled trial;

Death before reaching the eligibility criteria;

Hydrocortisone treatment at the time of enrolment;

Chronological age > 28 days.

characteristics.interventions:
Infants at planned extubation were randomised to:


nHFOV for extubation (n = 4):nHFOV settings were as follows: 

Pmean 8 cm H2O;

Frequency 9–10 Hz;

Amplitude 20–30 cm H2O;

I:E ratio 33:66.

nCPAP for extubation (n = 2):nCPAP settings were: 

PEEP 8 cm H2O;

Flow 7–8 L/min.

After extubation, appropriately sized binasal prongs were applied to the patient (Infant Nasal Prongs, Fisher & Paykel Healthcare Ltd., Auckland, New Zealand) and connected to a heated humidifier (MR850, Fisher & Paykel) and a neonatal ventilator (VN500, Drägerwerk AG, Lübeck, Germany, or Leoni Plus, Heinen & Löwenstein, Bad Ems, Germany) using the manufacturer approved heated‐wire ventilatory circuit. The ventilator remained the same before and after extubation. The FiO2was set to maintain SpO2at 90%–94%. Within the limits, the physician was free to adjust ventilator settings.

characteristics.outcomes:
Primary outcomes


PaCO2at 72 hours after extubation (time frame: 64 hours to 80 hours)

Secondary outcomes


Blood gas analysis results at 2 hours after extubation: pH, PaO2, PaCO2and base excess;

Blood gas analysis results at 72 hours after extubation: pH, PaO2and base excess;

Successful extubation within 72 hours;

Airway obstruction due to highly viscous secretions within 72 hours;

Treatment failure within 7 days, defined as meeting at least 1 of the following criteria: 

A sustained PCO2> 80 mm Hg and pH < 7.20 confirmed by arterial or capillary blood gas analysis despite maximum ventilator support;

An FiO2> 0.6 to maintain SpO2at 90%–94%;

Reintubation.

Reintubation within 7 days;

Total duration of mechanical ventilation until discharge;

Total duration of supplemental oxygen until discharge;

Rescue treatment (if the nCPAP infants developed treatment failure but did not need immediate reintubation, nHFOV was provided as ‘rescue treatment’. In the HFOV group, any non‐invasive rescue treatment could be provided);

Blood gas analysis results at 2 hours after switch to "Rescue Treatment": pH, PaO2, PaCO2and base excess;

Incidence of common adverse effects of prematurity (IVH III°‐ IV° (Papile 1978), surgical NEC, pneumothorax, pulmonary interstitial emphysema, PDA requiring surgical closure, ROP requiring laser treatment or injection of bevacizumab, or both, death or moderate‐to‐severe BPD (Jobe 2001), at 36 weeks' GA, PVL).
